As Barbara wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/25/2004 at 02:16:19 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>In WI, approximately 44% of all residents with either HIV or AIDS 
>have AIDS.  If there are 1,797 AIDS cases in WI, approximently how 
>many HIV cases are there in WI?
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>I changed the 44% into a decimal and then multiplied that by 1,797, 
>and I got 790.68.  I was wondering is ~791 the answer to this 
>problem.  If not, what am I doing wrong?

Hello Barbara,

If h is the number with HIV and a the number with AIDS, then

[a/(a+h)]*100 = 44.

We are told that a=1797.  So,

[1797/(1797+h)]*100 = 44.

So,

h is about 2287.09


